    <title type="html"><![CDATA[FlicekBirney2009-NGSReview]]></title>
    <link href="http://bingw.github.com/blog/2012/09/09/FlicekBirney2009NGSReview/"/>
    <updated>2012-09-09T14:02:00-05:00</updated>
    <id>http://bingw.github.com/blog/2012/09/09/FlicekBirney2009NGSReview</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<h3 id="sense-from-sequence-reads-methods-for-alignment-and-assembly">Sense From Sequence Reads: Methods for Alignment and Assembly</h3>

<p><em>Paul Flicek &amp; Ewan Birney</em></p>

<h4 id="abstruct">Abstruct</h4>

<p>review of alignment and assembly algorithms</p>

<h4 id="background">Background</h4>

<p>quality versus cost tradeoff:</p>

<ul>
  <li>de novo sequencing: longer reads</li>
  <li>resequencing: high coverage, paired-end reads</li>
  <li>mapping TF binding site/location of modified histones: <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chromatin_immunoprecipitation">ChIP</a>, short reads</li>
  <li>DNase-seq: limited to only 20bp of informative sequence</li>
</ul>

<p>Different error characteristics: </p>

<ul>
  <li>Roche 454:insertion or deletion errors during homopolymer runs</li>
  <li>ABI SOLiD &amp; Illumina/Solexa: errors toward the end of the read</li>
</ul>

<h4 id="alignment">Alignment</h4>

<p>Alignment methods(tradeoff between speed and sensitivity):</p>

<ul>
  <li>hash table-based implementations</li>
  <li>Burrows Wheeler transform(BWT)-based methods</li>
</ul>

<p>Alignment procedure:</p>

<ol>
  <li>heuristic techniques</li>
  <li>accurate alignment alogrithms(Smith-Waterman)</li>
</ol>

<h5 id="hash-based-alignment-methods">Hash-based alignment methods</h5>

<p>Sepecially for short reads. methods include:</p>

<ul>
  <li><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?holding=npg&amp;cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;list_uids=18714091&amp;dopt=Abstract">MAQ</a>:
  From the first 28 bp of the read, MAQ program builds 6 hash tables corresponding 
  to seeds of (length = 8, weight = 4). scans the reference genome against these 
  hash tables. This ensures that all hits with 2 mismatches can be found. 20 hash 
  tables required if get all 3 mismatches.</li>
  <li><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?holding=npg&amp;cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;list_uids=18227114&amp;dopt=Abstract">SOPA</a></li>
  <li>Illumina’s unpublished ELAND algorithm</li>
</ul>

<p>These have recently been joined by:</p>

<ul>
  <li><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?holding=npg&amp;cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;list_uids=19461883&amp;dopt=Abstract">SHRiMP</a>:
  use a <a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?holding=npg&amp;cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;list_uids=16597241&amp;dopt=Abstract">q-gram</a> approach, (require mutiple sapced seeds per read</li>
  <li><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?holding=npg&amp;cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;list_uids=18684737&amp;dopt=Abstract">ZOOM</a>:
  manually constructed spaced seeds of weight 14 to enable the detection of up to 4    mismatches in 50-bp reads</li>
  <li><a href="http://genome.ucla.edu/bfast/">BFAST</a></li>
  <li><a href="http://bioinformatics.bc.edu/marthlab/Mosaik/">MOSAIK</a>:
  hashes all positions in the reference genome and uses a ‘jump database’ to 
  efficiently locate information in the hash table and thus reduces memory 
  requirements by approximately two-thirds over a naive implementation.</li>
</ul>

<h5 id="burrows-wheeler-transform-methods">Burrows-Wheeler Transform methods</h5>

<p>use the FM index data structure, retains the suffix array’s ability for rapid subsequence
search. Much faster than their hash-based counterparts at the same sensitivity level.</p>

<ol>
  <li>the sequence order of the reference genome is modified using the BWT(reversible)</li>
  <li>the final index is created; it is then used for rapid read placement on the
genome(memory-intensive)</li>
</ol>

<p>softwares:</p>

<ul>
  <li><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?holding=npg&amp;cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;list_uids=19261174&amp;dopt=Abstract">BOWTIE</a>:
  Reported 30-fold speed increase over hash-based MAQ</li>
  <li><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?holding=npg&amp;cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;list_uids=19451168&amp;dopt=Abstract">BWA</a></li>
  <li><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?holding=npg&amp;cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;list_uids=19497933&amp;dopt=Abstract">SOAP2</a></li>
</ul>

<h4 id="assembly">Assembly</h4>

<p><img src="http://bingw.github.com/images/paul_alignment.png" alt="de Bruijn graph" /></p>

<ol>
  <li>Sequence at top represents the genome, which is then sampled using shotgun sequencing in base space with 7-bp reads.</li>
  <li>the k-mers in the reads (4-mers in this example) are collected into nodes and the coverage at each node is recorded.</li>
  <li>he graph is simplified to combine nodes that are associated with the continuous linear stretches into single, larger nodes of various k-mer sizes.</li>
  <li>error correction removes the tips and bubbles that result from sequencing errors and creates a final graph structure that accurately and completely describes in the original genome sequence.</li>
</ol>

<p>softwares:</p>

<ul>
  <li><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?holding=npg&amp;cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;list_uids=17908823&amp;dopt=Abstract">SHARCGS</a></li>
  <li><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?holding=npg&amp;cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;list_uids=17893086&amp;dopt=Abstract">VCAKE</a></li>
  <li><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?holding=npg&amp;cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;list_uids=18349386&amp;dopt=Abstract">VELVET</a></li>
  <li><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?holding=npg&amp;cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;list_uids=18083777&amp;dopt=Abstract">EULER-SR</a></li>
  <li><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?holding=npg&amp;cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;list_uids=18332092&amp;dopt=Abstract">EDENA</a></li>
  <li><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?holding=npg&amp;cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;list_uids=19251739&amp;dopt=Abstract">ABySS</a></li>
  <li><a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?holding=npg&amp;cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;list_uids=18340039&amp;dopt=Abstract">ALLPATHS</a></li>
</ul>

<h4 id="disscusion">Disscusion</h4>

<p>List of sequence alignment software: <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_sequence_alignment_software">wiki</a>, <a href="http://seqanswers.com/forums/showthread.php?t=43">SEQanswers</a></p>

]]></content>
